34.5%, respectively. Metastases at time of diagnosis had a 14.1% prediction 
value for a 3-year survival rate. Tumor extension to the vena cava (21 patients) 
affected survival in a significant way (55.8% at 3 years). A definite tendency 
towards lower stage and grade was observed in incidentally diagnosed RCC (11%). 
In conclusion, stage, grade, nodal and venous involvement as well as metastases 
at the time of diagnosis have a significant prognostic value in RCC. These data 
and the lack of early diagnostic methods for RCC suggest the routine use of 
renal ultrasonography in clinically asymptomatic patients during examination for 
suspected abdominal diseases and in high-risk patients (Von Hippel-Lindau 
disease smokers).

